deck_name: Burning Abyss - Block Dragon Varient (Master Rule 2020)
deck_excerpt: It would be an understatement to say this deck doesn't abuse the ability to freely summon monsters. While this deck is a bit old, it's still a menace
deck_description: If you thought wrapping your head around my RDA list from a fortnight back was hard - yet alone yesterday's True King Dinosaurs - today's list will fry your brain like an egg cracked onto an Australian street. I present to you - my Burning Abyss deck (ft. Block Dragon and friends). When I was originally brainstorming for what deck to do - I thought about running Burning Abyss on its own: in theory this deck could work out, however playing with a couple of test hands and comparing the results was rather shocking and disappointing. Shocking in the fact that this deck was clearly better - going X-2. And disappointing in the fact that I would then have to remake the deck. Playing this deck is rather simple. It strays away from how regular BA play - summon 3 copies of Dante, Traveller of the Burning Abyss - going into Beatrice and pass. This deck can utilize Block Dragon to its advantage: ending on boards such as Abyss Dweller, Fossil Dyna, Block Dragon, Saryuja and Beatrice. The main and simple concept is to get enough monsters to use block dragon - and to keep on special summoning. A lot of the cards in this deck have re-occurring effects or ones that allow them to bring themselves forward while also somehow plussing. You can make easy negate using cards like Giant Rex or Gallis the Star Beast. Again, like most combo heavy decks - this relies on how optimally you open. You could also easily end on a Hydralander for extra disruptions during your opponents turn. A good EARTH attribute monster that not many people take seriously is Kumongous. Not many people suspect Kaijus, especially from a combo oriented deck. If you want to go for the OTK with Borrelsword, you can rid your opponent of their ace card without having to worry about negations. This could become an out to cards like Dragun of Red-Eyes which arguably will become problematic if its announced in the TCG. Overall, this deck deserves a strong 6.5/10. It pushes through negates like crazy with a million ways to start your combos and even more ways to extend. While being a going 2nd deck, you can OTK your opponent with minimal effort. The only problem is it falls flat mid-combo. Starting it is not a problem - but finishing it definitely is. Luckily, this deck is pretty rogue so your opponent might not always Ash Blossom an important card - but when they do, it hurts like hell. So much so that chainblocking sometimes comes in clutch for you to end your opponent. Still one of the most fun decks I've yet to play, even if it's ever so slightly complicated..

deck_excerpt: A fun, fast, and consistent way to make your Power Rangers
deck_description: This is my second take on the amazing Super Quant strategy. I am a big fan of this strategy due to its extremely unique playstyle, and amazing card art. Without further ado, I would like to walk you through some of my card choices and what the strongest combo lines are.  To start I play a going first variant with a going second variant in the side deck. Basically, if you have to go second game one that's okay you should still be able to play, but going first is preferred as a lot of the extra deck choices are meant to sit on the field and prevent OTK's if you brick. This includes cards like white aura dolphin which can be made with psychic wheelder and blue layer. This card allows you to soak up a few attacks if you have a blue layer in the grave. You can switch it out for Goyo Guardian if you are going second. The other really big going first cards are the artifact cards. In the main deck I play one Scythe and one Morraltech. I also play one lancea in the side. I play three sanctums so that you can play desires and still have a chance to draw it, as well as the two trap trick so that you can draw into it even easier. The artifacts work decently in this deck because Grampulse can destroy spell and traps on your opponent's turn if it has blue layer as a material. That's pretty much it for the going first cards, you can take all of these out if you are going second for the cards that rely more on your opponent playing.  Now for how you want to use each of the Super Quant cards.  Red Layer- Opening this cards means that you probably won the game. You almost always want to summon him first unless your hand is extremely stacked. Both effects are once per turn but you have a lot of ways to get him in the grave (ie white layer, or any of the Dangers). You special summon any super quant from the grave when he is sent, which can include the mechs. This guy goes to grave a lot so make sure you shuffle multiple copies of him back with blue layer if you can.  Always play 3.  White Layer - The newest super quant monster allows you to really unbrick your hand if all you have drawn is one other super quant. You can normal the other one and special this one for free. If it's blue then you can make a grampulse for free. If it's green then you just special this and get its effect. Red is probably the worst one to pair with white just because the discard may not be live for red. Either way, White layer is very versatile and puts Alphan back in your hand when it goes to the grave. This can be used to help you turbo magna off the field spell, or it can help you rebuild a board on turn two. Play 3 as well.  Blue Layer - Blue layer is used for two things: searching the field spell, and shuffling back red. With that being said Blue layer is the easiest to get in a mech so Grampulse will almost always be on board. You play three cause you need the recursion, and there is no real way to search it.  Green Layer - Green is sort of lack luster. Unless you are playing a spellcaster variant with summoner monk he isn't very useful. You don't want to use his graveyard effect often due to the fact that you have to throw a super quant out of your hand. The one good way to do this is to send Green and White off of Alphan, and put Alphan in your hand then discard it again. This is a free plus one, but its not all that useful. In addition, Aeroboros is, in my opinion, the worst of the mechs. It is decent now in the link era, but with MR5 I see it being less useful. I only play 2 but you could play a third.  Alphan - This little bunny is so great for the strategy. The only time it's bad is when you open only it and White Layer, but that's part of why you're only playing two. On top of that White Layer lets you recur it from the grave for free so you don't even need to waste your blue on shuffling it back in. He is always in your hand so you don't need to play 3.  Thats pretty much it, this deck can easily and consistently make the boss and one other mech to help support it. You can spin monsters left and right with Magna and it is so fun to do. On top of that, it is non-targeting, non-destruction, and he is unaffected by card effects. Oh and did I mention that he can stop your opponent from adding cards to their hands if it has 6 materials.  This deck was decent before and now with master rule 5, it has a lot of potential to be rouge.  Hope you enjoy and please leave a comment below on what you think I could change.

deck_excerpt: This deck allows you to turbo out Final Sigma like its nothing; using only three monsters to crunch your opponent like numbers on a calculator. Truly
deck_description: What an awesome deck. For those of you guys who aren't familiar with Mathmechs - a deck that 'recently' came out in the TCG in the set Mystic Fighters - it is simply another cyberse deck: however, it specializes in spamming the board with monsters and going into one of the most broken cyberse synchros in order to OTK your opponent. Geomathmech Final Sigma not only has the ability to double its attack during damage calculation - but with its one turn boost using the effect of Mathmech Multiplication - can easily deal damage exceeding that of 10,000 Lifepoints. Unlike my Crusadia build from a while back - which you should still check out as it specializes in some bonkers combos to annihilate your opponent Equimax - this deck can ruin your opponents career in just a few simple steps (all depending on your hand of course) The easiest and most simple combo only really relies on you having two cards in hand. What you'd want to do to kick-start your combos is normal summon Balancer Lord. This card is a great starter monster and easily searchable off of cards like Cynet Mining. What it allows you to do is for the cost of only 1000 LP, conduct another normal summon of a cyberse monster - so using his effect, you can bring out Mathmech Nabla. It has a very nice effect that allows you to pop your other cyberse monster and bring out the card that enables it all; Mathmech Multiplication. This card can make your Nabla a level 8 -  and since its a tuner - 4 + 8 = 12. Thats some maths that even your 36 year old algebra teacher would be proud of. So now that you have made Final Sigma - you can use Multiplications effect from grave and boost his attack to 6000!! Conditionally, you're opponent might have something that would negate your combo - Apollousa, Abyss Dweller. But fear not; because you run a set of cards that not many people respect in today's format - Kaiju's. If your having problems with a card your opponent controls - just use Interrupted Kaiju Slumber. Or just straight up Gameciel them if you have him in hand. Either way, it shouldn't be too hard to break boards with cards in your hand - so the OTK is still very viable. Going first this deck obviously suffers slightly -  but thats part of the reason why I run Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax in the extra deck. You can benefit easily benefit off of the Link engine; special summoning two mathmechs and going into Link Disciple and Link Devotee in order to draw 1 and get two tokens on field. After that you can use a token to make Linkuriboh and then I:P Masquarena using disciple and the kuriboh on field. Using kuriboh's second effect - you can bring it back from the grave using your other token and on your opponents turn make Avramax. Overall, this deck deserves a good 5/10. It's not the best deck out there - and like all OTK decks falls flat to handtraps. Sadly, the most we can do protection wise is hope we draw called by the grave. Still, this deck can manage to survive going first and hopefully pull off the OTK next turn, so it does have the safety aspect Crusadia lacked in my opinion. Still this deck is a good breather from the past two decks - being simple and surprisingly semi-budgety. I'd recommend this deck to those interested in OTK's or just people getting into the competitive scene. Be sure to watch out for tomorrow's deck as its going to be a powerhouse. Definitely something to look forward to so stay tuned for that.

deck_name: ABC Turbo - ft. Union Driver (Master Rule 2020)
deck_excerpt: An easy-to-pull off and consistent way to end on ABC and Cyber Dragon Infinity. With all this new indirect support: ABC are at an all time high. I spe
deck_description: Where do I even begin? This deck is outrageously good. Even for my standards - this deck can turbo out negates like they were nothing. I have yet to feel so passionately about a deck like this. It's generic, strong and consistent as hell! There will not be a time where you cant make Cyber Dragon Infinity - and with the new indirect support announced, this deck will ruin your opponent and take you to the top! I'll be giving you a full breakdown on how to combo-off with this deck and vanquish your opponent off hope in just a few simple steps: trust me, it's as easy as ABC. Before I give you a rundown on how the deck works; I'd like to go over the engines that I've decided to play in this undefeated union of cards. The main deck only consists of the primary four, with a sub-engine implemented as well. The engines are as follows: the ABC engine, the Gadget engine, the Symphonic engine & the Danger! engine. All are assigned with a basic focus in mind - establishing solid negates. The ABC engine has been implemented in order to, quite obviously, turbo out your ABC-Dragon Buster (the main card in the deck). This pairs nicely with the gadget engine, as using the effects of Silver Gadget and Gold Gadget respectively, you can special summon pieces of the fusion monster from your hand. The symphonic engine has simply been put there to get an extra level 5 on board -  thats why the ratios between Guitaar and Miccs are 3/1. And of course the Danger! monsters are simply there to get a free body on board to go further into your link plays: making I:P Masquarena or Apollousa. The little 'sub-engine' I'm also referring to, is the triple Galaxy Soldier that I run. I'm using the term very loosely, so its not really an engine and  more rather just three cards that are searchable. If you don't have a clue about the two new support cards - Gizmek Yata & Union Driver - what they do is allow you to both extend your ABC plays and your Infinity combo. What Yata allows you to do is tribute your normal summoned monster and bring this card out onto the field. Then you can immediately after perform another normal summon, however you cannot summon monsters that are not the monster you just summoned's original type until the end phase. This is very good as it allows you to get a 2050, level five body on the field and perform another normal summon, however, this card locks you out of your Danger! engine while also stopping you from playing your other crucial negates from the extra deck. Union Driver's ability however is also very, very broken! This card allows you to equip itself to a monster you control (preferably your Assault Core, Buster Drake or Crush Wyvern) and then either a) unequip itself and special summon it to the field or b) banish itself from the field and equip a level 4 or lower monster from your deck thats a union type. This is obviously very good as it can make summoning ABC a lot easier, and since its level five you can also benefit off of its special summon ability. In conclusion, this deck deserves a powerful and hard 8.7/10. It might not be as meta as it used to during the ancient times of Master Rule 3, but it still is a great competitor and quite frankly a big sleeper deck in the new format. I think it has very good odds on topping one or two regionals - especially if we get Union Driver imported into the TCG rather quickly. The only shame with this deck is its brick factor. You mainly want the field spell in order to properly combo off - but with the amount of monsters its not allows easy. I'd consider maybe running a Set Rotation in the side deck along with a target in order to access it easier. I also know quite a few people that run Planet Pathfinder. While going through this build originally, I ran a few copies but it just seemed too cloggy and more like a waste of a normal rather than a searcher. Still, this deck is a force to be reckoned with - and will punish your opponent if needed!

deck_excerpt: Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram is a strong card that doubles as blanket protection from targeting, and a pseudo Zoodiac Drident. Searching its own recurs
deck_description:
December 2019 Top 4: Aromage Generaider Synchro

What deck did you play and why?

I chose to play Aromage Generaider this cup, though you could also call it Aromage Synchro. Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram is a strong card that doubles as blanket protection from targeting, and a pseudo Zoodiac Drident. Searching its own recursion (or more monsters) is also a big plus. On top of that, I realized that Draco Berserker of the Tenyi and the Generaider cards are incredibly strong, so I decided to run cards to facilitate them. My deck probably could have emphasized the Generaider side a little more, but it ran well enough without them.

What tech choices did you play?

Psi-Reflector is an incredibly strong card that I don’t think people have been taking advantage of. Being able to go into any generic synchro from level 6 to 9 off one card is incredibly useful. Specifically, I got a lot of use out of being able to flex between Marjoram, Berserker, and CQD. Past that I played a small Dino Engine, and a small Zombie engine to facilitate Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram. I found that both were better than the Genex or Supay engines people had been running. I also chose to play a Danger! engine to help unbrick hands and play through disruption.

How did you prepare for the meta, and would you change anything going forward?

I expected Generaiders to be relevant, though I didn’t build for them quite enough. Had counted on being able to use Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram to pop Generaider Boss Stage, but Nidhogg, Generaider Boss of Ice says "no" to Synchro Monsters a little too well for me. Should probably have played another take-control card or main decked Mystical Space Typhoon. Past that I didn’t really know what to expect that would give me too much trouble, so my side is a little too heavy towards a pendulum matchup I never had.

How were your matchups?

Really not terrible. Main issue was that my deck has a difficult time going second, cards like Nidhogg or really any disruption means I can’t get into my synchros, which means I’m usually left with an attack position Psi-Reflector or Armageddon Knight. Not exactly the best position. Luckily, the Dangers help mitigate this issue, and I run enough backrow that losing out on a first turn synchro usually doesn’t mean I’m out of the duel. Next month I might pick up another engine to help fix this issue. Over the tournament, I found that a lot of decks have a hard time getting around a live Marjoram, and the ones that don’t have issues with it usually have an issue with Generaiders or Berserker. Was a lot of fun piloting the deck in some of the matchups, top cut especially!

deck_excerpt: I played Lunalight Zoodiac, because it's the December cup; I intended on taking it easy and wanted to experiment with a different deck during Christma
deck_description:
What deck did you play and why?

I played Lunalight Zoodiac, because it's the December cup; I intended on taking it easy and wanted to experiment with a different deck during Christmas time. Turns out my list wasn't as casual as I thought it was going to be, since I made second place!

What tech choices did you play?

I played some pretty stupid ones. Wall of Disruption was in there, because I was high on Duel Links. I had CyDra in the side for the first time in a while (usually in the main deck). I took them out of the main because LunaZoo plays always hit the summon limit. Lunalight Serenade Dance was ok, though I never ended up using it in testing. Luna Light Perfume was always a better choice to mill with Foolish Burial Goods (or Zoodiac Combo if I already had access to Perfume). Ran Crackdown over stuff like Lost Wind and Solemn Strike because Crackdown would always be live if I drew it mid-game. I wanted simple backrow that I could count on to disrupt plays.

How did you prepare for the meta, and would you change anything going forward?

Mystical Space Typhoon, Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit, and Twin Twisters were my main deck, because I was very afraid of Generaider. That did actually come up, and handed me a win against Generaider in top 8 to the guy that was undefeated in swiss. So, for this format, I wouldn't change that. There's a lot of room for improvement with this list, but I'll leave that to the LunaZoo masters.

How were your matchups?

Either very straightforward or extremely difficult. Due to the nature of LunaZoo, there is no middle ground. If you can't answer a Zoodiac Broadbull, with Zoodiac Whiptail under it, and some strong backrow, you're gonna lose pretty quickly. If you can deal with that and keep recurring your resources, you'll probably win. I went X-2 in swiss, but got revenge against one of my losses in top 4 (Aromage Generaider Synchro). Ironically, I lost the final to someone I beat in Swiss (Blue-Eyes). GGs to all my opponents and I am pretty elated to be in the top 2 for the umpteenth month in a row!

deck_excerpt: I played Blue-Eyes, since it has consistent access to some of the most powerful cards in the format, like Chaos Dragon Levianeer, Number 95: Galaxy-Ey
deck_description:
December 2019 1st Place: Blue-Eyes White Dragon

What deck did you play and why?

I played Blue-Eyes, since it has consistent access to some of the most powerful cards in the format, like Chaos Dragon Levianeer, Number 95: Galaxy-Eyes Dark Matter Dragon and Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon. I love summoning Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star, and this deck let me do just that.

What tech choices did you play?

I opted to play a much more controlling version of Blue-Eyes, which played more trap cards, such as Torrential Tribute, Lost Wind, and Dark Factory of Mass Production. I have found that one big threat, backed up by a strong spells/traps, is much stronger than two big threats, with no backrow. The summon limit really prevents any heavy first-turn monster combos.

How did you prepare for the meta, and would you change anything going forward?

My Trinities were not spent optimally; in the future, I would try to better spend them. Some cards like Draco Masters of the Tenyi were never used. I often ended up siding out my Vessel for the Dragon Cycle, despite it being one of my Trinities.

deck_excerpt: With the new and fantastic Shaddoll support being out and ready to be imported into the TCG, I thought I'd join one of the most consistent archetypes,
deck_description: Reading back on my previous daily submissions, I've seen myself slightly fall into the YugiTuber rabbit hole. Essentially, whenever I post a deck, I like to tell you guys about the good bits - as thats the main reason why I post this sort of stuff. However, even I almost get myself muddled up in a sense that I almost make it sound like every deck is Tier 1 amazing: which a lot of the times isn't the case. So today I've decided to reverse the psychology behind my deck and tell you all the flaws I faced when making the deck, to show and encourage you to make your own build of this archetype tailored to how you like it. First thing that came up when putting together this set of cards, is the ratios. My original build saw quite a lot of dangers, which ended up being slightly bricky for this deck - as I ran too little ways to open up my extra deck and get the combos going. Thats why I'd recommend keeping a strong balance between the Shaddoll monsters and the Danger! cards - allowing you to open optimally way more and truly combo off into your negations like Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess or El Shaddoll Winda. You want to always max out on the semi-limited Dangers! as, their effects are the better ones out of all of them - and keep the level 8's at a low. The reason I don't run extra negation with cards like Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy or some solid protection + a pop effect like Dingirsu - is because you only run the level 8's at a minimal - this is due to a) them being not that helpful towards the end board and being simply bodies and b) if you have two level 8 Danger! monsters on board - you should be beating down your opponent. I'd say the Shaddoll fusion monster line-up is pretty stiff so theres not much room for change in that category. You want to always max out on El Shaddol Construct. This is due it to be a very powerful 2800 body that instantly pops special summoned monsters and has a built in Foolish Burial thats obviously really good with Shaddolls. The new card, El Shaddoll Apkallone, is very good during the grind game - thats why you only want one due to it being situational. And winda is a standard disruption of sorts with it locking your opponent out of special summoning. Overall, this deck deserves a hard-earned 6.3/10. Definitely not my best deck yet but a strong and consistent one for sure. It's pretty good at stopping your opponent, with the added boost of the dangers helping you out in making some pretty strong boards. Depending on the match-up, this deck could be a very tough competitor - plus, it uses one of the most fan favourite archetypes currently in the game. Could see this getting a cute regional top or two - but I doubt it will ever impact the game in such a drastic way like other support thats come out in the past, but it still will leave mark; I don't doubt that.

deck_excerpt: I played going second Mekk-Knights for the December 2019 cup. It's pretty much the same deck I've been playing for a while now.
deck_description:
What deck did you play and why?

I played going second Mekk-Knights for the December 2019 cup. It's pretty much the same deck I've been playing for a while now.

What tech choices did you play?

This deck was basically designed to be as anti- backrow and machine as possible, which would have been great against past meta decks like Kozmo and Traptrix, but I wasn't as prepared against big chungus decks like Blue Eyes. I also didn't expect Nidhogg, Generaider Boss of Ice to destroy my deck that badly.

How did you prepare for the December 2019 meta, and would you change anything going forward?

Going forward, I'll probably side the spell & trap hate, and prepare a better side deck.

How were your matchups?

I won against Noble Knights 2-0 Round 1, Salamangreats 2-1 Round 2, Thunder Dragons 2-0 Round 3, and "Phantom Fish" 2-0 Round 4 in swiss. Then I anticlimactically lost 0-2 against Generaider Subterror in Round 5. I somehow managed to win 2-1 against Habro's Blue-Eyes Round 1 of Top 8, but wasn't as lucky in Top 4. Lost 0-2 against WuhTrain's Blue-Eyes. There wasn't much I could do that game.

Mekk-Knight is included to provide offense and search some support cards that contribute to summoning generaiders or going for the Secret negation lock.

The 2 loses I got were in swiss, against Anju's amazing Mekk-Knight Dark-stuff deck. Honestly, that matchup was all skill. I just wasn't on par with Anju. To conclude all of my loses were on me - and not my deck - which I have optimized to hell by now.

deck_excerpt: A great and quite rogue way to use little-to-no resources and establish a good board of disruptions - not only is this deck quite optimal, but very bu
deck_description: It's back to studying for us here in England - so I thought I'd help you guys revise your Physics with some Super Quants! This is a very easy to handle, and budget deck for some of those deciding they want to start strong and mighty while also getting into competitive yugioh. This deck is very easy to learn, and plays slightly like Zoodiacs - just not as overpowered and very heavy on the colour theme. So without wasting another second, here's my take on Super Quants - featuring the new support. I've attempted to make this deck as coherent and consistent as possible: so I've mixed in two small engines to help out the deck so that it can run smoother, and decrease the chances of opening a bad hand. I run as little bricks as possible, with only 3 garnets in the main - and I've maxed out on all the Quantum monsters in order to get as many negates on board and as much synergy as I can get. The first engine I run - is a standard plant engine. I use Lonefire Blossom to get out my Ophrys Scorpio so that I can start the combo. The second engine of mine is a very compact Danger! engine. I only run five cards, mainly for draw and level three bodies. This also goes hand-in-hand with practically all my Quantum monsters - as they have effects that go off when they're sent to the grave. The new link monster also helps this deck out quite a few. Neo Super Quantal Mech King Blaster Magna allows you to draw a card whenever you special summon an extra deck monster to a zone he points to. This works really well with Magnacarrier, your ace card of the deck, as you don't lose any cards off of it's discard requirement. Meaning you can set-up a board with three disruptions for no cost so long as you have your field spell on board. This meant that I had to add an Emergency Teleport in order to summon Blue Layer and get to search. King Blaster Magna also brings himself back from the grave once he's destroyed, however you won't have those arrows in place so it will mean you must discard to make optimal negates. All of the different negates disrupt your opponent in some way. However - you could only do it on your turn unless you use a Super Quant of the right colour as material. Grampulse allows you to pop a backrow card of your opponents. This is very good for decks like True Draco that focus on the Spell/Trap zones. Mech Beast Aeroboros is practically a Book of Moon with legs; meaning it can disrupt a potential link play your opponent might make to stop their combo like Isolde, or just to negate an effect of some sort. Magnaliger allows you to pop an opponents monster which comes in handy if they're trying to make a play. This one is one of the more easier ones to summon as you usually have either Red Layer or White Layer on field. Finally, and by far the best one, Lusterrex. This card allows you to simply negate a monsters effect. Its a in-archetype apollousa except for only 1 negate. Either way, all four of these xyz's monsters are really good and with this build, you can usually end on 3 without losing any card advantage. To be frank, this deck is a nice 5.3/10. It's a pretty mild deck and doesn't require much skill to tackle - which is a blessing in disguise. The cards go for cheap, so its a big win for budget players. The archetype in my opinion is very underrated and deserves more support. Tune in tomorrow because I've got a very interesting decklist as part of my daily upload. Hope you have a great rest of the night, evening, day or morning!

deck_excerpt: Weather Painters using the WindWitch engine to make scarier first turn boards, which alongside backrow support can provide solid control and a beatsti
deck_description: Weather Painters using the Wind Witch engine to help make scarier first turn boards by making Crystal Wing, which can provide solid monster negation and a beatstick with decent protection to help buy time till you get Rainbow out. If you've never played weather painters before, the basic gist of their gimmick is that they use their spells and traps to gain unique effects of which they banish themselves as cost for, then return the following standby phase. This effect lets them work well with dodging removal effects from the opponent - as well as many good board wipe cards you may use yourself, such as Dark Hole, Interrupted Kaiju Slumber, and especially Torrential Tribute. The deck primarily functions as a stun deck, with it's primary "win condition" being make Weather Painter Rainbow to non once-per-turn negate anything and basically prevent your opponent from doing anything. The deck use of a variety of floodgates that work well within their strategy. -Anti-Spell Fragrance works well alongside Rain Canvas - since you can bounce back the set spell cards to your opponent's hand, preventing them from activating them. -Rivalry of Warlords also fits well, since all the Painters are Fairies (be careful not activate it prematurely in this build since you do play wind witches/crystal wing tho). -Skill Drain is a Weather Painter staple in all builds is by far the best trap in the deck. It works wonders with painters, since they banish themselves to activate their effects. In short, they still work under the effect of Skill Drain. And if you ever needed it gone for whatever reason, you can send it as cost with Thunder Painter and facilitate it's effect to place another Canvas straight from your deck face up. You play the 1 copy you can right now, but should it ever come off the limited list years from now, immediately bump that ratio up. -Imperial Order is also a good floodgate that is important in freezing out spell heavy decks like Sky Strikers, but it can also turn off your Spell Canvases too so it's kind of a give and take. Other tech cards that work well with this deck are -Pot of Extravagance: Unfortunately still stupidly expensive, but if you can afford it you should play it. Viable budget backups that can still somewhat work are Shared Ride and Upstart Goblin. Desires or Duality is not recommended... -Kaijus: Instant removal, but with an added benefit within this archetype. You can tribute over your opponent's monster, then use a Painter monster with Thunder Canavas's effect to bounce that Kaiju back to your hand for repeated usage. Any Kaiju can work, tho I personally prefer Gadarla particularly in this build due to the wind witches restrictions that may come up on occasion. -Valhalla Hall of the Fallen: Instant special summoning for all of your painters. Works incredibly well with Thunder or Aurora and can kick start plays alongside Snow. -Drowning Mirror Force: Given how often Painters banish themselves, it's quite common to deliberately leave yourself open to a direct attack, which works well with Drowning. Good for baiting offensive OTK decks and clearing the board in general, and while I don't prefer main decking it due to being matchup reliant you should always leave some space for it in the side deck. -Topologic Bomber Dragon: Other than Gumblar (cus that's never getting unbanned) all of the Topologic monsters make for excellent alternative boss monsters that the deck can make without too much hassle. Bomber basically become a quick play Dark Hole when paired with a painter and Rainbow Canvas. The same goes for Trisbaena, tho a bit less regularly since it'll remove your backrow too (which in most cases isn't optimal since the painters gain their effects from their backrow). So if you accidentally banish all of your Rainbows on accident with Extravagance, or your opponent has an established field that needs instant clearing: Bomber is a very good alternative boss monster that is very easy to obtain, play and summon. -Leviair the Sea Dragon: Probably the only Xyz monster worth playing in the deck. Generic Rank 3 that can bring back your banished Painters that aren't able to come back due to getting Ash Blossomed during the standby phase. Can come in clutch if you really need an important Painter back like Aurora for the protection. Not summoned a whole lot, but like a band aid it's good to have around.   Overall, this deck is pretty fun but also semi-competitive. It's able to go up against most casual decks, and even give the meta a run for their money if you play it right. Good luck, and have fun with em.

deck_name: Time thief Sky striker (updated, MR5 ready)
deck_excerpt: Disruption and theft of time thief with the board control and consistency of sky strikers.
deck_description: A slight updating of my previous version of this deck with a few touch ups here and there to improve consistency along with newer support cards being added. Combos for the deck are your standard time thief and striker combos but you can make use of Area zero and time thief redoer by targeting it with the effect of area zero to search, then banishing the reoder until the end phase similar to what can be done with Raye.  Your other combos mostly resolve around controlling the board with time thief and using the sky strikers for consistency and rank 4 material and if needed banishing your redoer or destroying one of your rank 4's to use the removal striker offers.  One newer addition is Sky striker ace Sieg, The decks new rank 2. The combo round this is simply to banish one card your opponent controls then if possible get a level 4 on the field then use Sieg's effect to destroy Area zero to special another striker from the main deck to continue xyz plays.  More simple interactions is the potential OTK with utopia double which if it fails due to drawing the one of double or nothing it can be used with area zero for a search. Using Daigusto Emerald to put back your strikers link monsters back into the extra deck which is especially helpful with cards like Kagari and time thief Perpetua or any other xyz or link in general (though these are your main targets).  The side deck has been improved with added disruption and negation such as ways to remove problem monsters in niburu and the kaijus along with some match up based choices such as abyss dweller for Orcust and evilswarm nightmare for combo decks. The rest of the side deck is mostly optional cards or alternatives for the main deck based on preference.

deck_name: Court of the Crimson King (Gren Maju Stromberg)
deck_excerpt: High performance banish deck that centers around summoning Rank8s, controlling the board, and swinging for game with Gren Maju
deck_description: This deck is centered around banishing as many cards as many cards as you can without decking out, gaining the benefits of cards like Golden Castle of Stromberg and Gizmek Orochi, the Serpentron Sky Slasher along the way. There are in service to both Gren Maju Da Eiza and Topologic Zeroboros gaining massive numbers and being able to swing for game.  The deck also facilitates a consistence Rank8 engine. By not only using the Danger! monsters, you can utilize Gizmek Orochi and Stromberg's effect to special summon a Hexe Trude directly from your deck, allowing you access to Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star or the Galaxy Eyes package.  On top of that, you're able to access Gren Maju with much more consistency against it being milled to the banished zone by running an entire Red Resonator engine to easily Synchro summon into Brotherhood of the Fire Fist - Horse Prince to summon Gren Maju directly from the deck. You can summon Red Resonator with either Glife the Phantom Bird to pop a spell or trap, or Chaosrider Gustaph to get two free banishes from the GY.  Lastly, Topologic Zeroboros can be brought out easily with all the resources you'd be able to summon. If you able to end with Gizmek Orochi in the GY at that point, you can use Gizmek's effect in the GY at the right time to banish everything on your opponent's side of the field, potentially removing your opponent valuable resources. And on your next standby phase, Zeroboros special summons itself from being banished, and gains 200ATK for each banished card for both you and your opponent's sides of the field.  Remember, if you deck out before you win, you probably deserve it!

deck_excerpt: An original and great take on the deck. I run some pretty spicy techs that disrupt your opponent for pretty much no cost. This is by far one of my fav
deck_description: Okay, this is epic. For today's upload, I've managed to make a deck that I could quite gladly call fantastic. This is a deck that I am proud of in the fullest - using new, quirky techs to spice up the decklist and make it even more of an absolute game-ender. I've used the quite popular Zombie Lightsworns, and made them viable again in the new format. Surprisingly, this deck has gotten less popular and strong since the rise of master rule 4, but with the new 2020 revisions this deck has gotten amazingly good - being able to run cards like Jack A' Booran for some crazy disruptions. To start off - this deck is fire! I've managed to end on boards like: Borreload Savage, Hope Harbinger, Balerdroch, Jack A' Booran and Abyss Dweller. This deck mills like crazy, being able to bring out so many negates makes it unreal. The main monster you want to see in your hand is Raiden, Hand of the Lightsworn. This card allows you to mill freely and is also a level 4 tuner, meaning you can access borreload with ease. It's also searchable off of ROTA, so you basically run 4 copies of this card (ignoring the draw power). This deck can also deal a whole lot of damage going second - with the effect of Zombie World making all monsters in either players graveyard zombie type; cards like Shiranui Shogunsaga are a great way to dish out damage to your opponent. With his effect, you can target cards with over 3000 attack and deal just about lethal damage depending on your situation. Jack is also a card that profits off of this effect, as its a re-occurring shark cannon of sorts; allowing you to special summon a monster from either players graveyard. An impeccable card to play is Super Polymerization. This card combined with your field spell makes all cards a good target for Nethersoul Dragon. This usually leads to scooping, with your opponent setting up big monsters just for them to go to the graveyard and give you a 3k beatstick. In general, there are very little outs aside from backrow removal when zombie world hits the field. I also run a modest Danger! engine, like most of my decks nowadays...It allows you to draw and get more names in the grave, which is good as a lot of cards I run have an ability to plus off that. With its new release, Arknemesis Eschatos has managed to make an appearance. I run three copies of melody of awakening dragon, allowing me to search him and Levianeer - a card that instantly lets you pop 2 cards from your opponents side of the field. Over all, this deck is a whopping 9.1/10. I'm pretty confident in saying this might be a very sleeped on deck after July. Once we get our imports from Japan, this deck will be a force. This is one of my best decks yet, in my opinion, and has immense potential. It's its own thing and I can respect that - being able to create unbreakable boards with fun and original cards. I hope you'll fall in love with it as much as me!

deck_name: TKing Dino MR5 W/ Argosaurus (card notes + video) Updated post IB BAN and w/ Litho
deck_excerpt: Post IB ban with Litho. (STAR SHAMAN NEW PATH) Consistent build, avoided win more engines as hard as possible Featuring Argosaurus and Crocosaur,
deck_description:
Deck notes below, video here > https://youtu.be/-2F4GljpBkg Maindeck (40) Dinosaurs:
  • 2x Ultimate Conductor Tryanno - 3 is brick, you ll constantly need a second. Just an amazing boss monster, even better with Pentestag,
  • 1x Overtex Qoatlus - Only a madman would put this card at more, the deck consistently banishes 4 dinos turn 1 (not 5), his summoning condition does come up, you definitely have to run him but his pill searching job is now shared with Argosaurus, he was always a one off for me.
  • 1x Dogoran the mad flame Kaiju - Fire, dinosaur, Kaiju, triggers lost world.
  • 1x Dinowestler Pankratops - Keep in mind you can summon him off petitranodon, you can trigger lost world with him, he is not just a going second card in dinos
  • 1x Giant Rex - You mostly summon the tuner off Misc because Fiber is broken but often times you can summon both + if you hard draw a tuner then you always drop rex. He is a great draw with Pill, easy R4 Dolkka then protect your plays
  • 3x Souleating Oviraptor - Just be happy this card is at 3
  • 3x Miscellaneosaurus - this is why you don't need 1212839108 argosaurus / one for one. This card essentially special summons him from deck without wasting normal summon. Misc tutoring argosaurus means your best Dino starters now have a way of not only searching babies but also POPPING THEM
  • 3x Babycerasaurus - I used to run 3 dinos babies worth popping in your hand (counting petit), but with there being more ways of popping the 2 babies I play 4 (Tested 5 to much)
  • 1x petiteranodon - Hi Pankratops, yes he is a baby to.
  • 1x Jurrac Aeolo - a fire lvl 1 tuner thats all, eff doesn't matter, maybe once it will
  • 1x Jewel Beast Argosaurus - New card searches pill (searching caligo claw for infinite negate loop path is brick city and cringe af), there is no need to add bricks to the deck when he searches an engine piece anyway. You only need 1, (two level one targets for misc is all you really need)
Other Monsters

deck_excerpt: An interesting way to extralink your opponent. Won't be around for long but still - a good deck in it's own right, and definitely rewarding once you p
deck_description: Okay, this deck is simple. Like most Extralink decks currently in yugioh, it revolves around summoning a heck-ton of monsters and linking away to ultimately stop your opponent from using their extra monster zone, which in master rule 4 is a very, very important. So without hesitation: i'll explain all you need to know about this deck, and how to reach its amazing endboard. I guess the main focus of this deck is to, obviously, a) stop your opponent from using zones and b) pitching spyral mission cards. You do this mainly using the discard effects of cards you play such as Card Destruction or the dangers, but your main play is to Master Plan. With the new Dark Magician level 1 monster, spyrals have gotten in-direct support. Not only can you recycle two spells/traps from your hand - which ties in with the spyral traps - but also get a free body on field as well as ditch master plan to the grave. This is amazing, as with a plethora of spell cards this card becomes easily searchable - notably the card Where Arf Thou. The second big monster you want to see - spyral quik-fix along with spyral drones. You can special summon these monsters using one for one and, again, search them off where arf thou as your normal summon - once your souls combo has resolved. The dark warrior/malicious engine is in there, mainly for added consistency, but the deck would do just fine without it. So what's the ideal end board? The main endboard you'd hope to achieve is one that your opponent has quite little chance of breaking through. You obviously want to have double helix in your first extra monster zone as he is the main combo starter. Then you would want to resolve a 3-card Tri-Gate. You'd special summon him just below helix, & the way you'd do this is by having a Knightmare Phoenix on his left, and Ib on his right. The reason I run Ib over a popular card like Proxy Dragon, is due to the fact that you can summon it without really trying - and it has the additional protection from battle and card effects. Then right next to it you run a Knightmare Cerberus, for obvious reasons - and a Linkuriboh right above it, for extra battle disruption. Overall, I'd give this deck a solid 7.8/10. It fails to handtraps a lot, meaning you want to open Called as much as possible. Along with that: there's also the possibility of bricking, which happens rarely - but when it does, you're basically better off playing game 2 and 3. Still it's a fun deck to play and very rewarding once you pull it off - locking your opponent out from zones is, in my opinion, better than setting up a board of negates. I'll definitely be trying to do more master rule 4 decks before April brutally murders me, and I'll try to make a quirky lock out deck as well, so look out for that. Comment some deck ideas down below, I'd love to hear what you guys have to offer!
https://youtu.be/Y-GVjsQQGdI
In a nutshell, we're looking to pop boards and/or establish our own. Easy OTKs, and lots of draw mean we can see even our 1 of's at least every so often.

deck_excerpt: With the new Nemesis archetype announced: people are splashing it into every deck - but whats better than mixing an attribute based archetype with inv
deck_description: When I do my daily uploads, I try not to make a deck on an archetype I've already used - in b4 someone mentions danger! - but the synergy between these two is just too good not to be uploaded on here! This banished-based archetype allows you to not only plus, but to get some extra negates on field if you play your cards right; so with that being said, let me explain why this archetype is so good, and what can it do.  First of all, let me just state that this is a splash archetype. I do not see this doing well on its own - it has a nice gimmick and all don't get me wrong, but just not enough cards or good effects to make it worthwhile playing this set of cards by themselves. However: cards like Nemesis Corridor still do have worthwhile effects. You can shuffle back a banished card, like it states, and then use it as fodder for colossus. It's a really cool play, as it allows you to extend and put a restriction on your opponent. Corridor is also available as a target for Raidjin, another disruption. I won't necessarily bother explaining the Invoked combos - as I've covered them in the past.  I run the Striker engine for consistency, and it does the job pretty well. One thing I would want to mention is Protos - it's a decent card and enables targets for your nemesis monsters, but you'd usually side it out game 2 and 3. It's also a nice beatstick when it comes to it, but usually you manage to make a pretty decent control board. Also, when showing the deck to my friend I'd had come to mind that I should most likely clarify: Secure Gardna is the target for Mechaba - just to put it out there.  In the end: this deck deserves a good 8/10. It's nice, and definitely uses the nemesis archetype nicely. Over all, not the best iteration of Invoked, but hopefully you enjoy it and have fun playing the archetype.

deck_name: Danger Dark World Mk... Better Than Ever
deck_excerpt: Get a bit lucky.  Discard and special summon out the arse.  Win game?  Profit.
deck_description: Papa's got a brand new bag (except not really). >:D Ok, so in all honesty, this deck is my personal pet project. Has been for a couple years now, basically since the Danger! stuff came out. I sincerely believe the Dangers! can be good all on their own with just a few cards to help them along. No extra engine per se (except my 2 card Dark World Grapha Recycling Service, you can pry that from my cold, dead hands), just a lot of nice cards that play well with the discard-centric mechanics of the deck.  The primary goal is still predominantly the same, except now the deck also has no issue going first, but it's ability to dismantle bigger negate-happy boards relies more on destroy effects than it does... well.. Lava Golem. I mean, it's still there, in the side, since we don't need our normal summons if we side out Vainty's Ruler, but it's not center stage anymore, as it has been in previous iterations. No, instead we welcome two new players to the game; The Fabled Good Boi and Infinite Impermanence! Why? Because Cerburrel isn't once per turn, making him basically another Tsuchinoko to this deck (I.E. good for links and/or tribute summons) and for that unique flavor of removal that is Brionac, and because this deck loses hard, and I mean HARD, to Abyss Dweller. So we run a hand trap that can be used turn 1, or we can at least hope to see it in our opening hand going second. If you don't have Infinite Impermanence, you're probably a sane individual with more reasonable and/or varied hobbies, and you can use PSY-Frame Gamma for the same kind of protection. I opted for the trap because it's got more utility (especially going first or after turn 1) and because it requires only 3 spots instead of 4. Also I hate myself and am a connoisseur of poor life choices.  Going first for the deck, comparatively, is actually a bit of a better time than trying to break really big and obnoxious boards. It's a good time when you can end on a board like, say, Vanity's Ruler, I:P and Lancelot (so as you can negate any nasty Evenly Matched activation as well) and maybe a fodder card, for a Knightmare Unicorn response, but it's also very realistic with a bit of luck. Just remember that, if it's at all possible, your 5th summon should be either Vanity's or Azathot to make sure you don't get Nibiru'd to nothin' but nubs.  On to the extra deck! This is your main toolbox. Anything that can't be popped has to be dealt with from here. Fortunately, between the two Link 4's and Unicorn, you do have a fair few options in that regard, and as long as you've got a bit of luck with your random discards, link fodder is no object. And generally speaking, anything Soldier of Chaos can't deal with, Borreload can.  That's about it, really. I think each step I take with this deck is really only a half-step forward in most cases, but progress is progress. I'll be taking this to a Regional event this weekend, so I can see how it does and maybe do another update with what I learn. This entire description and deck list is mostly for my benefit (as I enjoy keeping a log of not only deck lists but also previous versions of this deck for posterity), but if anybody who deigns to read this has any comments, criticisms or fun words of encouragement, feel all kinds of welcome to speak up. :)  Cheers! And happy new years!

deck_excerpt: Ritual Beasts are better than they've ever been and FINALLY got a generic searcher. Updated for the New Master Rule.
deck_description: This deck is the best that it's ever been. With new support (direct and indirect) and Master Rule 5 coming up, this deck can go off with the full Ritual Beast Combo (3 Searches + Floating) or place down an indestructible Crystal Wing + some disruption as a backup plan. The deck has always struggled with consistency, but it can now do something more than -Summon a monster and pray- most of the time. Wynn allows you to search all of your Beasts (except Winda and Lara) or the Wind Witches or even Droll and Lock if you've already got the combo while dumping beasts in the grave to extend. I've been playing Ritual Beasts off and on since they were released and am very satisfied with this list.     A couple of things you should be aware of:  -The Wind Witches: They lock you out of summoning level 5 or lower Wind Monsters, so if you have Elder+Cannahawk/Pengu or like combo, don't use them. They are for the hands when you can't go off with RB's.  -The Dragon Ruler is to get dead Ritual Beasts out of your grave.  -For Experienced RB players: The Research Lab/Zefra Field spell thing was...neat, but with the limiting of Terra it's just not worth it anymore. Feel free to playtest it and tell me if it's any more consistent, but I don't think it is.  -For Players new to Ritual Beasts: This deck can be deceptively complex. I recommend finding some tutorials online. If you don't know, you can use Ulti-Cannahawks First Effect, then chain his second effect and summon back one of your targets. As long as one makes it to the grave, the search effect still resolves. Opening Elder + Cannahawk/Pengu should net you 3 searches or 2 Searches plus an ideal board (4 RB's + 2 Steeds). Also note that Ulti-Apelio is uneffected by everything when she attacks, so any attack boost it got is shut off (it's annoying). Just remember, practice makes perfect. YOU WILL MAKE MISTAKES. The deck is VERY rewarding to learn and get better at.     I've had a love for this deck for a while. I love the art, the cards, and the unique deck playstyle.  Feel free to leave comments and suggestions in the comments.  -
Giving this one a shot

deck_name: Sky Striker Orcust - ft. Broken New Support!
deck_excerpt: With the new support card announced - Orcust will be bolstered up to tier 0 is no time. This new monster allows you to instantly open into the ideal e
deck_description: First off, why? I have never used broken to describe a deck on my daily uploads: but what other deck can we call broken if not this one?! Konami have done the outstanding move of giving an archetype that's already broken - even more disgustingly amazing support. Mekk-Knight Orcust Girsu is by far the most fantastic Orcust card. It can work as an combo starter, and extender - and instantly allows you to start up your combo's with a token on board. The list I've made is a rather simple one - focusing on getting the Striker Orcust endboard as fast as possible: which happens nine times out of ten. But there are some insane combos you can make - seeing as though it is both a Mekk-Knight card and becomes a level 4 tuner, which enables ib like never before. An optimal engine you might want to play is also Scrap. The main reason I cut it was primarily because of Girsu's effect - doing the same if not more, and with the fact that Golem acted as a garnet which somehow I opened way too much! Still the ammount of monsters you normal summon reduces, but if you want to add it I'd recommend cutting the Zerovoros in extra, Mathematician and Phantazmay in main. An end board you might want to make is most likely Longirsu, Dingirsu, Cresendo and Babel with 1-2 orcust monsters in grave and a Gizmek orochi. With the new support, this practically isnt a challenge - so open well and your opponent might as well scoop. The second board you could make is I:P, babel and some monsters in grave. This instantly opens a way to nuke your opponents board with Zerovoros, and will usually end to passing back to you, and you getting 4K beatstick and your opponent being wide open. Which if you open another combo opener, could lead to a potential OTK. Overall: this deck deserves no lower than 9.8/10. Orcust are one of the most meta-defying engines out there, making top cut almost every YCS and Regional there is. With this new support: Konami have shown that this deck will not die, and continue to crush people one-by-one like bugs. As much as we hate this deck: It is one - if not - the best deck in the meta. There is no deck at this moment that can rise up to it, and I'm not surprised why. It has yet to have its fall from grace - despite everyone wanting it to. Can't wait to see this deck rise up to Tier 0 alongside Dragon Rulers and TeleDAD. Konami have made a big mistake...

deck_excerpt: Dinosaurs are back, baby! Bring on Eternity Code!
deck_description: Let me just start by saying Eternity Code and Master Rule 5 excites me more than a 5 year old in a toy store. Dusting off the ol' Dinosaur deck ready for April 1st, I've been playing around with different strategies for the deck. An example of this is the new Jewel Beast - Argosaurus. That bad boy is a 1.5 card combo to end on a Linkuriboh, a Rank 4 of your choosing, and either an Ultimate Conductor Tyranno OR Overtex Qoatlus. However, the main combo for this deck involves Ultimaya Tzolkin. Sounds insane right? But thanks to Master Rule 5, it is not only possible, it is the nuts. Ending on a board of Apollousa, a Level 7/8 Dragon Synchro, and either Ultimate Conductor Tyranno OR Overtex Qoatlus is nothing to laugh at. You can further extend this with a Naturia Beast if you have access to Giant Rex. Would I consider this Meta-Breaking? No. But it sure can be difficult for most decks to get around with the buff to Dimensional Barrier.  I will be happy to explain how this combo works if people ask for it.

deck_excerpt: Psy-frame Sky Striker control deck Gameplay session : https://youtu.be/O5C7HFkggvA
deck_description: Gameplay session : https://youtu.be/O5C7HFkggvA     Through banlists, Psy-Frame was indirectly hit by loosing 2 Metaverse and 2 Terraforming that are searchers of Psy-Frame Circuit, the key card of the archetype. So the Sky Striker Engine is usefull to add consistancy by generating draw power, CA and enabling more gameplans if we are forced to go second. The Psy-Frame monsters works as hand traps, they respond to particular actions to special summon themselves from the hand and special summon a Psy-Frame Driver from the hand/deck/graveyard to negate an effect or an attack and destroy the card (Psy-Framegear Alpha being the exception with it's tuto effect). The two monsters will be banished at the end phase if they remain on the field, and you can only activate this effect if you control no monsters. Psy-Framelord Lambda and Psy-Frame Circuit are the most important cards of the deck, the first bypassing the conditions of activation of the Psy-Framegear monsters and the second consisting on a rapid synchro summon using the two summoned monsters (there are 2 Psy-Framelord synchro monnsters that banishes themselves until the next standby phase to trigger their effect so you control no monsters anymore and can continue to resolve your Psy-Framegear monster effects from your hand even without controlling a Psy-Framelord Lambda). Psy-Framegear's effects can be stopped by Ash Blossom so be sure to use them at the good timings, but since they don't have others activation restrictions and will remain in your hand, you will be able to use them again immediatly.   The monster engine is built to countain the Psy-framegear that will be usefull in the most cases before siding, so we have 3 Psy-Framegear Alpha to respond to an opponent's summon and tuto, 1 Psy-Framegear Beta to negate an attack and destroy the attacking monster, 3 Psy-Framegear Delta to negate and destroy a spell, and 3 Psy-Framegear Gamma to negate a monster effect and destroy it. Psy-Framegear Epsilon isn't main decked because being able to respond to trap cards is mathematically more specific, so we'll side it to optimize the consistancy. 2 Psy-Frame Driver are enough to avoid bricks when enabling the deck to work even after banishing disruption effect. Blackwing - Steam The Cloak is a one card combo to gain access to Psy-Framelord Lambda : normal summon Cloak then link summon Salamangreat Almiraj to create a token that you'll tribute to summon Cloak from the graveyard, then link summon Psy-Framelord Lambda and use the newly created token to bring out a Linkuriboh and gain a little protection effect for your Psy-Framelord Lambda. Lastly Ash Blossom will slow down the opponent to handle it's boards more easily when starting second, and will back up the Psy-Frame monsters to prevent your opponent to come back by locking a tuto/specific summon effect. The spell engine countains of course Psy-Frame Circuit, and Sky Striker cards with some generic draw/back up. Psy-Frame Circuit allows instant synchro fusion when a Psy-Framegear's effect resolves, enabling synchro 7 and 8 summons during the opponent's turn since all Psy-Framegear are level 1 and 2 tuners, and sports a battle effect that discards a Psy-Frame monster to boost a Psy-Frame monster you control by the attack of the discarded monster (your monsters will be able to peak at 4000/5000 atk so you can bypass some specific beatsticks or protect yourself). The Sky Striker engine countains Engage to search other pieces of the engine and draw, Hornet Drones to create a token and summon Kagari that will recycle Sky Striker spells, Aterburner to destroy a monster then a backrow card, Widow Anchor to negate a monster's effect and steal it and Shark Cannon to banish a monster from the graveyard or take control of it. Note that if you have to be aggressive you can use the stolen monsters with Widow Anchor/Shark Cannon to rapidly summon a Borrelsword Dragon. Lastly we use Sky Striker Airspace - Area Zero because it can send a Psy-Frame Overload to the graveyard if we have one in the opening hand when being able to search a Sky Striker spell, it's equally a neutral target for Set Rotation. Terraforming and Set Rotation are field searchers to get access to your Psy-Frame Circuit, Set Rotation is good combined with Sky Striker Airspace since it won't give benefic effects to your opponent in most cases and can bring out Mystic Mine in some situations. Mystic Mine is a great card to temporize the game if we have a mediocre hand and is also an option to open the game if we go second so we can force out a negate or be safe to make our loops without being interrupted by monster effects. Lastly Foolish Burial Goods send Psy-Frame Overload to the graveyard from the deck and Upstart Goblin and One Day Of Peace are good neutral draw cards that litterally say that we play at 38 cards. We run only 3 trap cards, one Metaverse to directly seet a field spell from the deck so we have Psy-Frame Circuit or Mystic Mine during the opponent's turn, and 2 Psy-Frame Overload that can banish cards on the field and overall banish itself from the graveyard to tuto any other Psy-frame card. Note that Psy-Frame Overload can be chained to your other effects to protect yourself from some disruptive plays.   The extra deck is composed of level 7 and 8 synchro monsters that directly help the control gameplan of the deck and a little Link monsters base to concretise boards. First we have Salamangreat Almiraj and Linkuriboh that pairs with the Blackwing - Steam The Cloak combo. Psy-Framelord Lambda allows your Psy-Framegear's effects to resolve even if you control monsters, and tuto any Psy-frame card when one of your Psy-Frame monsters banishes itself (even if he leaves the field). Lastly Borrelsword Dragon is a way to go for aggressive plays/finishers in pair with Widow Anchor and Shark Cannon to use the opponent's ressources. The synchro monsters first countains Psy-Framelord Zeta and Psy-framelord Omega, level 7 and 8 monsters that can banish themselves to respectively banish an opponent's special summoned attack position monster and a random opponent's card from his hand until the next stanby phase. Zeta can also return from the graveyard to the extra deck to recycle a Psy-Frame monster. Omega can return from the graveyard to the extra deck to return any card from the graveyard to the deck so you can recycle specific monsters, and can return a banished card to it's owner's graveyard during the opponent's stanby phase so you can recycle your Psy-Frame Overload to gain extra tutos. The fact your synchro Psy-Framelords banish themselves means you won't contrl monsters anymore so even if you didn't summoned Psy-Framelord Lambda you will be able to use other Psy-Framegear effects, and when returning to your field they won't use your extra monster zones anymore. F.A. Dawn Dragster and Borrel Savage Dragon are a spell/trap negate and a negate all that will back up the Psy-Frame monsters or finish a board if you Don't control Psy-Frame Lambda. Black Rose Moonlight Dragon can bounce monsters to disrupt boards by directly cuting ressources, being a good weapon against fusion and synchro focused decks. Black Rose Moonlight Dragon is a great way to wipe entire boards, mainly if your opponent mostly his backrow. Finally Dragon Ogre Deity Of Tenyi is a good weapon against combo decks that will banish monsters and extenders to prevent comebacks, it can also attack two times in a row on special summoned monsters to add a little offensive power to the deck.   Now the side deck. It's mainly designed for going second games since we want to go first to set the field for our Psy-Frames to operate. Twin Twisters can destroy up to 2 backrow cards when potentially discard cards like Psy-Frame Overload, to have a better match up against decks using consistant backrow that could be annoying. Sky Striker Maneuver - Jamming Waves is also a searchable card that can destroy 1 backrow card plus 1 monster. Dark Ruler No More will neutralize combo deck's boards and let you free to set up your board. Artifact Lancea is a must have that notably stop Orcusts as well as Thunder Dragons. Psy-Framegear Epsilon is a card to add to countain decks using traps, and is also a good way to handle the most Dangerous floodgates against decks like True Draco. Stardust Dragon is a specific tech against True Draco that is a hard match up with it's floodgates and backrow that destroy our cards when sent in the graveyard, it has the advantage to stop True Draco's backrow secondary effects and counter Diagram. It tribute itself to resolve it's effect so since True Draco usually Don't run Called By The Grave, it won't be able to hit Stardust Dragon after it's effect resolution so it will come back later to permanently pressure your opponent's plays. Lastly Borreload Dragon is a way to bypass monsters like Avramax that would be a nightmare for the deck if your opponent is able to bring them out.

Ok Guys,  We want to draw or get access to Souleating Oviraptor, this is why we Main Extravaganz. With Lost World + Pankratops we can get access (Special Token, destroy Token, protect with Lost World, destroy Baby or Petiteranodon and summon Oviraptor) to our boi Oviraptor. We don’t play Pill, because it bricks hard. Handtraps: Ash is one of the best in this format, Crow is for Orcust match up, Inpermanence for negating floodgates!!

Misty Tredwell, known as Misty Lola in the Japanese version, was a character from Yu-Gi-Oh! 5D's. She is a fashion model, who could read someone based on their facial appearance. She was a member of the Dark Signers with the Lizard dark mark, but was returned to life following Goodwin's defeat. He wears a light purple formal shirt with a black cravat, vest, pants, and cape with golden stripes at the bottom and a red lining. He wears black boots with silver toes. He also has a pair of purple earrings with orange studs that resemble his old head and a blue diamond chip on his neck and back.

Galaxy-Eyes Deck (New Support)

This updated Galaxy-Eyes deck is mainly for bringing out Xyz monsters, such as Galaxy-Eyes Photon lord and Cyber Dragon Infinity, which can distrupt on your opponents turn.

Note: This is almost identical to my "Pure Galaxy-Eyes Deck (Post October 2019 Banlist)" deck profile (which yo can find on my profile). This will be an update to it and will mostly focus on the changes that's I've made.

 
  • Main Deck(Monsters) -
    • Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon(x3)
      • No changes
    • Galaxy Knight(x2)
      • No changes
    • Galaxy Soldier(x3)
      • No changes
    • Galaxy Wizard FROM (x3) TO (x1)
      • This card wasn't a strong normal summon. It usually got in the way of Galaxy Knight. I run x1 due to it being able brick-y. I should be used as discard material or if you know you wont normal summon on the turn (very unlikely) or it's your only normal summon, the use it. Its effect, allowing it to be level 8, helps Galaxy Expedition. If you have a Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon in the GY, via a Trade-In discard or The Melody of Awakening Dragon Discard, then you can use Galaxy Wizard to search Galaxy Trance and combo from there. Overall, I wouldn't run more than 2 at most.
    • Photon Orbital(x3)
      • No change
    • Photon Vanisher(x3)
      • No Change
  • Main Deck Additions and Removals(Monsters) -
    • Additions -
      • Galaxy-Eyes Afterglow Dragon(x3)
        • A wonderful card. It's pretty much a free special summon; it allows Trade-in and The Melody of Awakening Dragon to be more power. Its effects it great for Number 62: Galaxy-Eyes Prime Photon Dragon and Number 107: Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon.
      • Photon Thrasher(x2)
        • Pretty much replaced the x2 copies of Galaxy Wizard. It's a "Photon" monster, therefore it works well with Starliege Lord Galaxion. Also a free special summon. It's only at x2 because it's terrible if you get x2 in your hand or draw it for your 6th card, via Trade-In or form the Draw Phase.
      • Photon Advancer(x2)
        • A better version, most of the times, because you can actually normal summon it. Can be a free special summon, because you do x14 "Photon" monsters including (Photon Sanctuary). Great for RANK 4 summons or Link summons
      • Galaxy Brave(x2)
        • This deck runs more "Photon" monsters, therefore running this for free special summons.
    • Removals -
      • None
  Main Deck(Spells/Traps) -
  • Galaxy Expedition(x3)
    • No changes
  • Galaxy Trance(x2)
    • No changes
  • Photon Sanctuary(x3)
    • A free Galaxy-Eyes Solflare Dragon, allowing you to summon more XYZ monsters from the Extra Deck
  • Return Of The Dragon Lords FROM (x3) TO (x2)
    • Running 6 dragons and only having x2 is fine. This card provides protection but I feel like running x3 would be too much. You want to see cards that you can do something with instantly or cards that done need a setup.
  • Trade-In(x3)
    • No changes
  • Main Deck Additions and Removals(Spells/Traps) -
    • Additions -
      • The Melody of Awakening Dragon(x2)
        • You can add Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon and Galaxy-Eyes Afterglow Dragon. Just discard another copy of the Galaxy-Eyes Dragons or a Galaxy Wizard. x2 is perfect.
    • Removals -
      • Monster reborn FROM (x1) TO (x0)
        • It didn't do anything at the moment and was mainly used to discard things as you can do better plays without it rather than using it.
      • Called By The Grave FROM (x3) TO (x0)
        • This deck can play through hand traps pretty well because of thr free special summons. This card should be in the side deck if you really want it.
      • Galaxy Zero FROM (x1) TO (x0)
        • Same story with Monster reborn
      • Tachyon Transmigration (x3) TO (x0)
        • The deck needs more space for more useful cards which actually confirm that you'll get a board with 2 or more negates.
 
  • Extra Deck
    • Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Blade Dragon(x1)
      • No changes
    • Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon(x1)
      • No changes
    • Galaxy-Eyes Full Armor Photon Dragon(x1)
      • No changes
    • Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon(x1)
      • No changes
    • Galaxy-Eyes Prime Photon Dragon(x1)
      • No changes
    • Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord(x2)
      • No changes
    • Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy(x1)
      • No changes
    • Number 97: Draglubion(x1)
      • No changes
    • Cyber Dragon Nova(x1)
      • No changes
    • Cyber Dragon Infinity(x1)
      • No changes
    • Galaxy-Eyes Solflare Dragon(x2)
      • No changes
 
  • Extra Deck Additions and Removals -
    • Additions -
      • Starliege Lord Galaxion(x1)
        • Running level 4 "Photon" monsters. This is perfect.
      • Starliege Photon Blade Dragon(x1)
        • Not used as much but great for certain conditions and protection.
    • Removals -
      • Divine Dragon Knight Felgrand FROM (x1) TO (x0)
        • Didn't use it.
      • Thunder End Dragon FROM (x1) TO (x0)
        • This card was a place holder for any card you wanted to place instead. I just filled Starliege Photon Blade Dragon as a recommendation.
 
  • Side Deck
    • Personally, I think you should make it yourself. Side decks depend on the meta.

deck_excerpt: An overpowered, new rock-based archetype that surprisingly has no set playing style. This deck draws a fine line between versatility and splashability
deck_description: Hello! I'd like to apologize for the recent inactivity. I am currently resolving some issues IRL which I don't feel comfortable sharing - but I'll do my best to keep dishing out these awesome decks. I might not be able to upload daily however - so I've set myself a target of a new deck every other day. So with that out of the way, here's the card list.  Adamatia is a strong, independent archetype that archetype that focuses on...nothing? The reason this deck appeals to me a lot - not taking in to account that rocks finally have good support - is it's versatility and the ability to change playstyle on command. It is a synchro based deck that focuses on bringing out tuners, and searching/stacking your deck. I, of course, have decided to make a more-or-less negate heavy strategy: out of impulse of course. Due to them being rock monsters, Block Dragon works surprisingly well in this deck - thats why I run a 6 card engine. The main concept is to use level 4's like Gigantes or one of the eggs - to make Naturia Beast. What's great about this deck, is you most likely will always manage to find a way of summoning it. Instant fusion also helps out - making the level 3 earth attribute fusionist.  A really good tech card that works well with this deck - is Muddy Mudragon. Since it's a level 6, you can make this card at literally anytime due to the Adamatia monsters - with this, you can use cards like Destrudo and use its built in polymerization effect - making Dragun of Red-Eyes. That plus Naturia Beast and some disruptions with the Adamatia synchros and you've got a near unbreakable board.  In conclusion: I'd give this deck a solid 8.2/10. I really like the fact you can play this deck in so many different ways - using cards like Block Dragon to your advantage, and even playing it pure. In my opinion, it deserves all the hype its getting - and will definitely be a fan-favourite after April's new change. Great deck - hopefully konami puts out more bangers!

deck_excerpt: Powerful 1 card Stardust Dragon/Assault Mode combo Lots of revival with the Dragon Rulers Can also make a targeting protected Beelze of the Diabolic
deck_description:
Strengths: 

  • Powerful 1 card Stardust Dragon/Assault Mode combo
  • Lots of revival with the Dragon Rulers
  • Can also make a targeting protected Beelze of the Diabolic Dragons

Weaknesses:

  • GY removal hurts a lot
  • Can brick (lots of garnets)

Trinities:

  • One for One (Extra Unlimited Card)
  • One for One (Extra Unlimited Card)
  • Emergency Teleport (Extra Unlimited Card)
  • Emergency Teleport (Extra Unlimited Card)
  • Blaster, Dragon Ruler of Infernos (Extra Unlimited Card)

Comments:

Summon Psi-Reflector, use its effect to search for Assault Beast. Assault Beast searches Assault Mode Activate. Reveal Assault Mode Activate with Psi-Reflector to summon Assault Beast. Make Assault Beast level 7 with Psi-Reflector. Synchro Summon Stardust Dragon! On your opponent's turn, flip Assault Mode Activate to make Stardust Dragon/Assault Mode. Even if you have a garnet, you can still use the above combo (or just Psi-Reflector and a Dragon Ruler) to make Beelze of the Diabolic Dragons. Note that drawing Assault Mode Activate will still let you make Stardust Dragon/Assault Mode. Just Synchro Summon Stardust Dragon normally! We play a Trinity on Blaster, Dragon Ruler of Infernos, since he has the most ATK. This also lets us banish Blaster to search Burner, Dragon Ruler of Sparks, who can then summon the other Blaster. Other interactions of note involve using Tuning Gum to make Beelze of the Diabolic Dragons, to give it targeting protection. You can also use Cyberse Synchron to make Leo, Keeper of the Sacred Tree, with destruction protection. Finally, a cool tech I want to point out is Necroid Synchro, letting us make Stardust Warrior for free!

deck_excerpt: High chance of opening the Zoodiac Combo Maindeck banish removal Lots of cool plays
deck_description:
Strengths: 

  • High chance of opening the Zoodiac Combo
  • Maindeck banish removal
  • Lots of cool plays

Weaknesses:

  • losing whiptail to banishing removal hurts a lot
  • some number of maindeck jank cards

Trinities:

  • Fire Formation - Tenki (Extra Unlimited Card)
  • Zoodiac Broadbull (Extra Unlimited Card)

Comments:

  • Fire Fists are pure value cards
  • Rat, Thorough, Tenki, or Barrage, are all 1-card 2800 Banishing Piercer combos.
    • Mill Thorough with Rat (or NS it)
    • Make Zoodiac Tigermortar to attach Zoodiac Thoroughblade from GY
    • Make Zoodiac Broadbull to search Zoodiac Whiptail
    • Technical Play Tip: Don't attach Whiptail until you have to.
  • Sided Xyz Universe can make Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star using opponent's XYZ, or with your own Zoodiac Chakanine
  • Rank-Up-Magic Raid Force + Any Zoo = Raidraptor - Blaze Falcon, which is raigeki, which can then make Gaia Dragon, the Thunder Charger
  • Halfway to Forever can make Number F0: Utopic Future or Number 39: Utopia (and then Number S39: Utopia the Lightning) with Zoos in GY.
  • If you opponent tries to kill your Zoodiac Monster, chain Wonder Xyz to "negate" the removal.
  • If you start your turn with Broadbull, search Brotherhood of the Fire Fist - Swallow.
    • then make Zoodiac Chakanine to resummon Bull, then Tribute Summon Swallow.
    • This nets you a Fire Formation - Tensen (presenting a 2200 ATK Banishing Chakanine which can't be targeted by opponent's cards).
    • Alternatively, you can play and search Ultimate Fire Formation - Sinto, though I find this to be bricky.
  • If you draw Caius the Shadow Monarch, you can summon tribute fodder for it with Zoodiac Chakanine. He can also free up the EMZ.
  • Fodder for True King Lithosagym, the Disaster can be searched with any Zoodiac.
    • Make Broadbull, then search Zoodiac Bunnyblast or Zoodiac Ramram. Destroy Bull and the searched card.
    • Lithosagym will trigger their effects.
